Across all four years, small infill MLI Select projects generated an estimated 666 mandated-affordable units in the Edmonton CMA, with approximately 480 coming in the ZBR era (2024–2025), a period that also saw 2.6 times as many projects as the two years prior (see @fig-affordable-units and @tbl-affordable).

These are units where rents are contractually capped at roughly \$1,500 per month or below.

## Conclusion

Small infill is only one part of Edmonton's MLI Select story, but it is uniquely enabled by zoning. Large apartment towers were already permissible before ZBR. The 5–8 unit rowhomes could not exist in mature neighbourhoods until January 2024. Every one of the 283 small new construction MLI Select loans approved since ZBR represents a project that would have been illegal two years earlier.

Edmonton's Zoning Bylaw Renewal is delivering on housing affordability in a way that rarely gets discussed. By legalizing small infill development in mature neighbourhoods, the ZBR didn't just add housing supply, it unlocked CMHC's MLI Select program for a class of projects that previously couldn't exist. Those projects come with mandated affordable rents attached.

The pipeline continues to grow. The 104 small infill MLI approvals from 2025 represent projects currently under construction or about to break ground — adding to the stock of affordable units in Edmonton's established neighbourhoods.

This is what good housing policy looks like: a municipal zoning reform enabling federal affordable housing finance, delivering affordable homes in mature neighbourhoods with established street grids, amenities, and transit connections where demand is high. The question now is whether we can keep the momentum going.
